-- Alrosa Says Diamond Price Increase of 60% Doubles 2011 Earnings
-- B y   I l y a   K h r e n n i k o v
-- 2012-05-17T04:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-05-17/alrosa-says-diamond-price-increase-of-60-doubles-2011-earnings.html
OAO Alrosa,  Russia ’s state-controlled
diamond miner, said profit more than doubled last year after
average prices for the rough stones surged by 60 percent.  Net income rose to 26.7 billion rubles ($860 million) from
11.8 billion, Mirny, Siberia-based Alrosa said in a statement on
its website. Sales expanded 21 percent to 138 billion rubles.  The average price of rough diamonds used in jewelry gained
to $197 a carat in 2011 from $123, Alrosa said. Earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization rose 87 percent
to 65.2 billion rubles, while Ebitda margin reached 47 percent.  Rough diamond output grew 1 percent to 34.6 million carats.
De Beers Group, Alrosa’s largest rival, produced 31.3 million
carats in the period, it said in a Feb. 10  statement .  Alrosa’s debt declined by 6 percent to 95.5 billion rubles,
while its debt to Ebitda ratio dropped to 1.5 from 2.9.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ilya Khrennikov in Moscow at 
